5 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
6
7 Section 1. Section 3-2-101, MCA, is amended to read:
8 "3-2-101. Number, election, and term of office -- selection of chief justice. (1) The supreme court
9 consists of a chief justice and six associate justices who are each elected by the qualified electors of the state
10 at large at the general state elections next preceding the expiration of the terms of office of their predecessors,
11 respectively, and in a separate district by the qualified electors in that district at the election next preceding the
12 expiration of the term of office of the justice's predecessor. Justices hold their offices for the term of 8 years
13 from and after the first Monday of January next succeeding their election.
14 (2) After the general election in 2032, the chief justice must be selected by the majority vote of the
15 seven justices at the first meeting of the court in each year after a general election."
16
17 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Supreme court districts defined -- number of judges. (1) In this state
18 there are seven supreme court judicial districts, distributed as follows:
19 (a) First district: Blaine, Cascade, Chouteau, Fergus, Hill, Judith Basin, Liberty, Pondera, Teton,
20 and Toole Counties;
21 (b) Second district: Big Horn, Carbon, Carter, Custer, Daniels, Dawson, Fallon, Garfield, Golden
22 Valley, McCone, Meagher, Musselshell, Park, Petroleum, Phillips, Powder River, Prairie, Richland, Roosevelt,
23 Rosebud, Sheridan, Stillwater, Sweet Grass, Treasure, Valley, Wheatland, and Wibaux Counties;
24 (c) Third district: Yellowstone County;
25 (d) Fourth district: Beaverhead, Broadwater, Deer Lodge, Granite, Jefferson, Lewis and Clark,
26 Powell, and Ravalli Counties;
27 (e) Fifth district: Flathead, Glacier, Lincoln, and Sanders Counties;
28 (f) Sixth district: Gallatin, Madison, and Silver Bow Counties; and
